    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "act": "COLD OPEN",
      "t_start": 0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "The quantum harmonic oscillator is everywhere in physics. Molecular bonds, crystal lattices, trapped atoms \u2014 all of them. Why does one simple model fit everything?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "reveal"
      },
      "card": {
        "dek": "Every valley is a parabola if you lean in close enough",
        "eyebrow": "QUANTUM MECHANICS"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-potential-parabola/mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.56,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-potential-parabola/clips/B01.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-potential-parabola/mp3/beat-B01.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "act": "THE QUESTION",
      "t_start": 9,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Nature is full of complicated, lopsided potential wells. A perfect parabola predicts quantum energy levels equally spaced. Real wells are not parabolas. Yet the equally-spaced levels keep showing up. Why?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "reveal"
      },
      "card": {
        "dek": "Complicated wells predict complicated spectra. Parabola predicts equal spacing. Real spectra show equal spacing. Why?",
        "eyebrow": "THE QUESTION"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-potential-parabola/mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 14.45,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-potential-parabola/clips/B02.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-potential-parabola/mp3/beat-B02.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "act": "THE PROBLEM",
      "t_start": 19,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "A potential well can have any shape \u2014 asymmetric, lopsided, with cusps and bumps. Any smooth function drawn over a minimum.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "scan"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-potential-parabola/mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.97,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-potential-parabola/clips/B03.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-potential-parabola/mp3/beat-B03.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "act": "THE PROBLEM",
      "t_start": 30,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Taylor-expand the potential about its minimum. The first derivative is zero \u2014 that is what a minimum means. The linear term dies. What is left is a quadratic.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "reveal"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-potential-parabola/mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.16,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-potential-parabola/clips/B04.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-potential-parabola/mp3/beat-B04.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "t_start": 40,
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "Zoom into the bottom of any smooth well. Watch the well and a fitted parabola approach each other as the region narrows. At the minimum, they merge.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "zoom"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-potential-parabola/mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.14,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-potential-parabola/clips/B05.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-potential-parabola/mp3/beat-B05.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "t_start": 52,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "The effective spring constant is the second derivative of the potential at the minimum. That is the only number the parabola needs. The shape everywhere else is irrelevant for small oscillations.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-potential-parabola/mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.0,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-potential-parabola/clips/B06.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-potential-parabola/mp3/beat-B06.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "t_start": 63,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Every molecular bond, every lattice site, every trapped atom \u2014 each has its own complicated potential. But near the bottom, each becomes a parabola with its own spring constant.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-potential-parabola/mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.05,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-potential-parabola/clips/B07.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-potential-parabola/mp3/beat-B07.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "act": "THE IMPLICATION",
      "t_start": 74,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "The harmonic oscillator is universal not because nature is simple. It is universal because every minimum lies.",
